column1: 73210;instagram;2019-01-17 03:03:19;FALSE;"snowflake is the name i gave to my baby conceived from rape. i made the decision to terminate the pregnancy almost within the same week of finding out. i knew i conceived snowflake the same day the incident occurred but i was in denial. i denied it as i thought having taken the morning after pill within 12hrs took care of that possibility... when the doctor told me i was pregnant
column3: i burst out into tears and cried hysterically
column4: she gave me time to let it sink in. i was alone in a hospital bed and all i could think is how could i possibly be able to bring this baby into the world. ..

column1: conceived in a violent traumatic way and left the world in a heartbreaking way. i have never been pregnant before this
column2: i never knew what a major connection a person could experience  with another living thing before my snowflake üòûüò≠üò≠ ..

column1: i don't talk much about my baby
column2: i haven't really been given time to grieve... i can say it still tears my heart apart
column3: i know i made the best decision at the time
column4: with my chronic hip pain syndrome i don't even know how i could have carried snowflake to term.. regardless

column1: 73256;instagram;2019-01-17 02:32:17;FALSE;i finally actually sat down and watched one episode of the documentary... my heart is regretting it... i‚Äôm so hurt for these girls and their parents.... this hits a little close to home for me as i was raped when i was only 16 and the man that did it never went to jail not even for a night!!!... for anyone to think that this is ok or to think that it‚Äôs the girls fault is absolutely ridiculous! mark my words i will never listen to a song of his ever again... frankly it makes my skin crawl.... the hurt that you feel deep down in your soul is unlike any other and it never seems to go away... it can be masked and you can go on and live a semi normal life.....but the mental damage that it does never goes anywhere.... you will still not 100% trust a man.... you will still have anxiety about small stuff... you will still have outbursts of anger for no reason at all..... if you‚Äôre lucky enough you will never see that person again... i happen to live in the same town that my assaulter lives in... i‚Äôve seen him twice in the 15 years since that night and my heart drops to my stomach... i can only imagine what the survivors of r kelly go through... he‚Äôs so much in the public eye it‚Äôs hard to not see or hear about him!!! i pray for justice and i pray he will not ever hurt another... but most of all i pray for peace and for some kind of closure for the girls and their families!!and if there is anyone in my friends list who sees this and feels the need to comment and take up for that monster you will immediately be deleted and blocked.... sorry not sorry #muterkelly #timesup #metoo;;en;#muterkelly

column1: 73307;instagram;2019-01-17 00:51:36;FALSE;i have started an autobiography that will be finished soon! it goes all the way back to my childhood and talks about my depression starting young
column6: and how i overcame to be who i am today. i wasn't able to fully open up in my writing until i made the decision to be completely honest and open about everything
column7: no matter how hard it would be or controversial it would be. it's been bringing me back
column8: making me feel what i once felt
column9: giving me panic attacks and crying episodes
column10: but i won't stop until it's complete. if by my vulnerability i am able to help someone

column1: 73379;instagram;2019-01-17 00:25:53;FALSE;"everything happens for a reason right? but then we have those life events that leave us going uh ... what was the reason behind that? the divorce? an abusive relationship? loss of a child? sexual assault? ? what did i do so wrong in life to deserve that type of set back? well
column2: i'm here to tell you that you didnt....? you dont deserve any trauma that happens throughout life. i myself have been left sitting there wondering why?
i've realized these situations we find ourselves in are not our fault
column3: but they are events in our lives that are to help build us to be better..... to teach us that we are made for more! we are given our mountain to show others that it can be moved. quite possibly even give you the strength and knowledge to support and guide someone else how to move their mountain.

column1: i know me personally. i grew as a person. i stood up for myself. i found help. new friendships to lean on. ive been able to help others with the knowledge. but also
column2: i learned i'm stronger then i knew i was and braver then i thought i was. hard situations and gods timing
column3: and it's highly possible that by not being where i thought i should be
column4: ended up putting me exactly where i was meant to go. these moments helped shape me into who i am today. my life events and traumas placed me on my life path to meet certain people
column5: expierence new things all in their own timing. i have the best support system that i know is safe and comforting. the individuals in my circle are supposed to be in my life at this very moment. the relationships are right where they are supposed to be in development
column6: and each one has its own purpose in my self growth. .

a confession/ a secret/ adultery/no shame
a short poem by yours truly
a streak ran down my forehead
the scar of an obedient daughter
a devotion of my love as a child
i felt naked in the cold air
to those who met my gaze
memories that never rise to the surface
an open palm cracked in two
grains of salt stung the wound
i am given a bouquet of roses
repulsed i take them by the stem and squeeze
the birds lament for the weak creature
who limps among the dead flowers
the snakes on her head become quiet
the stillness settled in my broad cheeks
the rocks in my pockets weighed me down
one by one they are thrown
an open palm cracked in two
grains of salt stung the wound

no anger/ no grudge/ no resentment only forgiveness :: mercy
only god can touch me now

column2: monia mazigh shared some penetrating thoughts and criticism on the relationship between the hijab and feminism.
about 29 women decided to stand up publicly in the streets of iran and remove their hijabs. they were protesting the compulsory hijab imposed on women since the islamic revolution in 1979.

these women were described as ""heroes"" and their protests branded as ""courageous."" even though i strongly believe that these spectacular actions play into the western obsession with the hijab and muslim women's bodies
column3: i consider these actions courageous. however
column4: on the other side of the spectrum
column5: when zunera ishaq legally challenged the harper government to be able to take the citizenship oath while wearing a niqab
column6: she was not called ""courageous"" on social media.

column2: a canadian scholar originally from iran who was arrested in 2016 by the iranian regime and later released
column3: wrote about how iranian women lived under the shah dictatorship before the islamic revolution
column4: and explained how many iranian women suffered when the shah banned the veil in an attempt at ""modernization."" many women stopped going out because they didn't want to be uncovered. they stopped socializing and were deprived of going to places such as public baths or even working outside
column5: thus losing social and economic status.

column1: my point isn't to defend some choices over others or to claim that wearing a hijab is harder or more courageous than removing it. both are difficult and dangerous decisions depending on the countries where women live. however

column2: we have to be very careful about our assumptions. while of course the pink tax exists and it is not difficult to see it we just need to go out to our local supermarket. it is important to consider that some products cost more for women than for men for legitimate reasons. taking a normal bottle of shampoo for example
column3: the shampoo for women is more likely to contain things such as different fragrances or different types of moisturizers which are usually not included in men‚Äôs products. this is why it is very important to be careful about denouncing the pink tax especially to the people who do not understand it well. always consider that there might be a reason behind this difference of price. .

it's been about a week since news broke about a figure skating coach in the area who is facing charges of criminal sexual contact with a sixteen-year-old girl. his name is andrew lavrik and he is currently suspended by the professional skaters association. this news came a few days after accusations against john coughlin.

column4: and even ask why it took three months of these interactions before the girl came forward. this stuff is never neatly wrapped or easy to understand. the bottom line is that it should not happen.

column1: here is the thing: most girls grow up knowing how to spot creeps. groomers
column3: are not as easy to pick out. they make victims feel special. (who doesn't love that? especially when it comes from someone you admire.) they also have a psychopath-like way of drawing people in and normalizing situations.

column2: the rise of #metoo has been a reckoning. both men and women are having to reevaluate their experiences and beliefs‚Äîones they've decided are ""just the way things are"" for as long as they can remember. i think this is good for us. i am also happy that women are finally being believed.

column1: please listen to ""five women"" on this american life. listen to the ""believed"" podcast. listen to the women in your life. when people cross the line

column2: accountability has been the hardest part‚Äîlearning how to have a voice in this‚Äîto have the bravery to say ""please don't ‚Äî"" or ""this is not okay."" i am still learning. hopefully this is a step in the right direction.

column1: 73657;instagram;2019-01-16 20:11:38;FALSE;"i can be changed by what happened to me. but i refuse to be reduced by it.

almost 20 years have passed since i was raped at 17 by my then-boyfriend and his best friend and although i would love to sit and write to you about how i had a specific cure that suddenly made me feel better about everything
column2: or a 'lightbult' moment that made everything disappear to then transform me into the woman i am today
column3: i sadly do not because the fundamental truth is healing or any kind of awakening is not linear.‚Ä©this is for those of you who have begun your journey to find yourself again after rape
column4: or sexual trauma or abuse. maybe your part way through your journey and are feeling lost
column5: or feel like you've hit a wall. wherever your at
column6: i just want to tell you that i've been exactly where your at now and even tho it doesn't feel like it
column7: i want you to know that it does get better because at the beginning of my journey
column8: i thought i had no hope. i was lost. i had no answers
column9: i didn't understand fully what i was thinking or feeling and the thought that anyone else would fully understand me seemed impossible. i remember the times that i tried to seek out answers and i failed many many times
column10: so often that i thought i was always going to remain broken. that was until the day that i decided to give myself a break by giving myself lots of time
column11: self love & patience for it was only then that i was able to find the answers that i was looking for. they were hidden deep inside of myself
column12: waiting to be found so i could put myself back together again ü¶ãüíñ#survivor #metoo #domesticviolenceawareness #rapesurvivor #blogger #truth #butterflysparklesandbullshit #realtalk #withbravewingssheflies";;en;#metoo

73798;instagram;2019-01-13 11:18:58;FALSE;"statistics relating to gender based violence against women
more than half of all the women murdered (56%) in 2009 were killed by an intimate male partner
between 25% and 40% of south african women have experienced sexual and/or physical intimate partner violence in their lifetime
just under 50% of women report having ever experienced emotional or economic abuse at the hands of their intimate partners in their lifetime
prevalence estimates of rape in south africa range between 12% and 28% of women ever reporting being raped in their lifetime
non-partner sexual violence is particularly common
column2: but reporting to police is very low. one study found that one in 13 women in gauteng had reported non-partner rape
column3: and only one in 25  rapes had been reported to the police

column1: south africa also faces a high prevalence of gang rape
most men who rape do so for the first time as teenagers and almost all men who ever rape do so by their mid-20s
south africa is one if the capitals of gender based violence in the world. such problems are perpetuated by rape culture and casual indifference by men and women in the public
column2: political and private spheres. a problem to be confronted and dealt with!

column1: 73832;instagram;2019-01-16 18:33:45;FALSE;"end of 2014: working in restaurants and bars.

column2: looking out for me and providing me with food
i was unable to lean on blood family
column3: but the bond i felt with these people were much stronger.

column1: during the first months of arrival
column2: a man grabbed my vagina at a club. i yelled
column3: which excited him more. he was a japanese mc
column6: and moving to do it again and again. just as i was about to hit him
column7: a us military guy pulled me aside. ""hey
column9: this is the culture here. you need to be the one to move aside.""

column1: being at the bars months later
column3: and witnessed worse. colleagues would say ""no
column5: knowing that they could lose a customer if they fight back.

column2: where women are trained to be a friend and companion for the evening. some men loved this false sense of intimacy
column3: and took it as an invitation to do as they wish.

column1: it was both people i knew
column3: my strong female friends taught me that it was not okay.
screaming at these men to stop
column4: did not stop them. the only time i ever had someone stop

column3: my reactive brain that was trained overseas
column4: is ready to fight. i often need to smoke cannabis to slow down my fight/flight/freeze response when i get triggered
column5: as it would be easy for my muscle memory to mistake an ignorant canadian man for an aggressive international one.

column1: my traumatized mind doesn't want to loose this aggressive training
column2: as i feel it would protect me in the future. although
column3: the most mentally damaging gropings happened while i was sober
column6: i am grateful for these experiences

column1: 73918;instagram;2019-01-15 22:55:34;FALSE;"i love a good bandwagon. #tenyearchallenge ‚ú® i was 16 in 2009. i was the second slowest on the cross country team and insisted on wearing skull print scarves. ~emo~ if you will. everything i owned was covered in otis‚Äô fur (see first pic). i‚Äôd been dealing with anxiety and depression for a few years but thought it was just ‚Äúangst‚Äù. so i memorized all the words to this is how it goes and screamed along with @billytalentband. i just made a facebook account and was thoroughly into farmville‚Ñ¢. my dad got joe anderson to sign one of his headshots and i just about died [(he played max in ‚Äòacross the universe‚Äô) (i still have it.)] i was a virgin and had yet to kiss a boy. i‚Äôd kissed a girl at 14 but was told that didn‚Äôt count. my period was still so bad it qualified as menorrhagia despite being put on the pill at 14. unlike the majority of my peers
column2: puberty did nothing for my breasts. my hair had too many layers and i couldn‚Äôt leave the house without the most padded bra imaginable. i hated my body and had just begun what would be my decade long struggle with anorexia and bulimia. both a way of coping with anxiety and a belief that if my boobs insisted on being small
column3: i‚Äôd make the rest of myself small too. it seems screaming to canadian punk no longer did the trick
column4: so i resorted to starving and purging. i was already naturally quite boyish and gangly
column5: so this only made me look even more like a stretched out gumby. ‚ú®

column5: harassment] since the ala fire set by a stalker
column6: our community has been reliving some collective and individual traumas done by both insiders and outsiders; myself included. in fact
column7: i remembered an assault that i had actively put out of my mind for years. what i've been trying to do is not only raise awareness about the amount of stalking
column10: and sexual assault that happens in this community
column11: but also offer support for people it's happened to
column12: and see if we can start a conversation about solutions. one solution is convention security
column13: but it doesn't solve the problem of ""missing stairs
column14: and there's only so much we can legally do to bring attention to certain individuals or conventions. all i know about the rest is that to bring change to this community
column15: we need everyone's help. we need to call out unacceptable behavior before it gets bad. we need cis men to call out other cis men. we need everyone to educate themselves on statistics of the aforementioned. we need to heal together and move forward.

column1: i had a tweet about how ""cosplay is not consent is not enough"" that got bigger than i anticipated and it's been causing me to think about all of these things at once. i want to help
column2: but that's been emotionally a lot
column3: especially following a whole weekend revolving around the topic through conversations with ohayo guest erin tillman. yes
column4: i want to shine light on the topic
column5: but it's been filtering through both cssn and personal accounts
column6: and i never wanted us not to be able to manage the weight we've decided to carry.

column1: i have content from magfest and ohayocon to share
column2: but it won't be for a little while. i need a bit of a break from this conversation because i can feel myself becoming upset from feelings of guilt
column4: and secondhand trauma. in the meantime
column6: cosplayer-ssn.org/resources.php is a good place to go. please take care of yourselves. thank you for being wonderful listeners and followers. üì∑@robert.tate.photography

column1: 73951;instagram;2018-11-02 16:14:32;FALSE;"classysilhouette is a #realwoman. this is the cover of an album by @classysilhouette titled #queenofqueens that was released in 2015. the reason the album is titled #queen of #queens is because of how much adversity #classysilhouette has been confronted with since she entered the music business as an #independent #singer #songwriter & #producer. the new way to success seems to be computer hacking. her files were hacked a few years ago & she began to see other producers & artists using her lyrics
column2: graphic designs & video concepts as if they were their own. after much analyzation classy silhouette realized that she was the victim of discrimation & sexism. producers stole her work & used it to produce other artists & began to spread rumors & lies to confuse people so they would not want to work with her but attack her character. classy silhouette always felt as though females should reference themselves as queens & not hoes & b***ches. the @classysilhouette.queenofqueens #album is symbolic of that movement. a new female artist @nenamarcella was introduced on the album. she is known for powerful voice. because there was so much jealousy & hate there were many attempts made to sabotage this movement. people were manipulated to think negative things about classy silhouette it was defamation of character. now over time the truth is being revealed about & that classy silhouette produces all of the music & videos for her company more capers have been conjured up to defame her name or degrade the crown that she wears on her head. it is not about a genre of music or a town. she is wearing it to encourage women to respect themselves & each other as queens. that is why classy silhouette is the queen of queens. all of the misinterpretations come from evil seeds planted by the people who hacked her & stole her work. they want you to think all of those things so you won‚Äôt know the truth.
